ves beyond widely circulated deficit models of respectability, bringing together discourse analysis with a close reading of technological interfaces to develop nuanced arguments about how “blackness” gets worked out in various technological domains. As Brock demonstrates, there’s nothing niche or subcultural about expressions of blackness on social media: internet use and practice now set the terms for what constitutes normative participation. Drawing on critical race theory, linguistics, rhetoric, information studies, and science and technology studies, Brock tabs between black-dominated technologies, websites, and social media to build a set of black beliefs about technology. In explaining black relationships with and alongside technology, Brock centers the unique joy and sense of community in being black online now.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Black Studies (Global).2bisacsh  aBlack Twitter.  aBlack culture.  aBlack cyberculture.  aBlack digital practice.  aBlack discursive identity.  aBlack identity.  aBlack kairos.  aBlack memetic subculture.  aBlack online identity.  aBlack pathos.  aBlack respectability politics.  aBlack technocultural matrix.  aMan Crush Monday.  aWestern technoculture.  aWoman Crush Wednesday.  aappropriate technology use.  ablack technoculture.  acall-out culture.  acolored people time.  acritical discourse analysis.  acritical race theory.  acritical technocultural discourse analysis.  actda.  adigital practice.  adiscourse analysis.  adogmatic digital practice.  adouble consciousness.  ainformation studies.  ainteriority.  ainternet studies.  aintersectionality.  ainvention.  alibidinal economy.  amemes.  amobile phones.  amodernity.  anetworked counterpublics.  aonline community.  aonline ide